{"title_page": "Esan North-East", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          =Esan North-East\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = [[Local Government Areas of Nigeria|LGA]]\n|motto                  =\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            =\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_mapsize=\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       ={{flag|Nigeria}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[States of Nigeria|State]] \n|subdivision_name1      =[[Edo State]]\n|subdivision_type2      =Capital\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      = \n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =  \n|established_date       = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           =\n|area_land_km2            =\n|population_as_of               =2006\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone               =[[West Africa Time|WAT]]\n|utc_offset             = +1\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = \n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       =  \n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Esan North-East''' ([[Uromi]]/[[Uzea]]) is a town and [[Local Government Area]] located in [[Edo state]] of Nigeria with an estimated population of 119,346.<ref>[http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/Connections/Pop2006.pdf 2006 National Census (Nigeria)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704042011/http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/Connections/Pop2006.pdf |date=July 4, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n<br />\n==Geography==\nEsan North-East is bordered with [[Atani]] by [[Ubiaja]], [[Ebhoiyi]] by [[Igueben]], [[Ivue]] and [[Obeidu]] by [[Irrua]], [[Uzea]] by [[Afemai]], [[Amendokhian]] by [[Ugboha]] with towns in all its surroundings.\n\n<br />\n==Government==\nThe Esan North-East Local Government Area is divided into two constituencies. Constituency 1 comprises Wards 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5, while constituency 2 comprises Wards 6, 7, 8, 9, and 10, making a total of 10 (ten) political wards represented by two representatives in the [[Edo State House of Assembly]].\n\nEsan North-East is a Local Government Area located in Edo state of Nigeria with an estimated population of 119,346.(2006 Census). The figures are believed to be much more higher than that now. The headquarters of Esan North East is Uromi. According to Wikipedia, Uromi is the largest and most populated Town in Esan Land, and the second fastest growing town in Edo State.\n\n<br />\n== Political Structure ==\nEsan North East has eleven political wards and two state constituencies (two state House of Assembly seats). Constituency 1 is made up of Ward 1 to 5 while Constituency 2 consists of Ward 6 to Ward 11.\n<br />\n<br />\n== Traditional Kingdoms ==\nEsan North East is made up of two gazetted kingdoms and they are:\n\n* Uromi Kingdom\n* Uzea Kingdom\n* Uromi Kingdom has ten wards(Ward 1, 2, 3, 4 ,5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11) while Uzea Occupies one ward (Ward 6)\n\n\n== Economy ==\nUromi is the commercial hub of Esan Land.The main town popularly referred to as Garage is the commercial nerve centre. The Uromi main market boom with commercial transactions of various kinds every day, all year round, including public holidays and yuletide. Aside Garage, a huge chunk of Esan North East\n\npopulace are predominantly farmers.\n<br />\n<br />\n== Education ==\nEsan North East has the following higher institutions of learning\n\n* The National Institute of Construction Technology Uromi.\n* St Camilus School of Midwifery Uromi\n* National Open University Uromi Study Centre\n* Palm City Polytechnic Uromi\n\nApart from the above, the current best secondary school in Nigeria is situated in Uromi Town. Lumen Christi International High School Uromi was rated by WAEC as the best secondary school in Nigeria on account of the school's excellent performance in the 2016/2017 WASSCE.\n<br />\n<br />\n== Health ==\nThe Uromi Central Hospital(formerly General Hospital) was established to meet the health needs of the people. Aside the Central Hospital, there are government owned health centres and private medical outfits across the LGA including St. Camilus Hospital, Oriafo Hospital, Udegbe Medical Centre to mention but a few.\n<br />At medical zone Uromi, Esan North East LGA Central Hospital Uromi. \n<br />\n== Notable Citizens from Esan North East ==\n\n\nEsan North-East has produced well-known individuals who are popular in both state and national level. These include:\n\n*[[Chief Anthony Enahoro]] - one of Nigeria\u2019s foremost anti-colonial and pro-democracy activists\n* Archbishop Ekpu\n* Cardinal [[Anthony Olubunmi Okogie]]\n* High Chief Dr. Tony Anenih (CFR), (Iyasele of Esanland)- A strong leader of the ruling PDP. Elder Statesman, Former Minister of Works/Housing, and the Prime Minister of Esan Land.\n*Rtd, Air Vice Marshal Anthony Ebehijele Okpere\n* Ehia Olu. AKHABUE\n* Pastor Raymond Okpere\n* Professor, Mike Obadan\n*Professor, E. Okoeguale.\n*Architect Mike Onolemhenmhen (Former Minister Of Works)\n*[[South-South_Nigeria_Rugby_Football_Federation|Flourish Itulua-Abumere]]\n* Dr. Joseph Itotoh (Former Minister for State, Internal Affairs)\n\n* Chief Arc. Dr. Mike Onolememen, Political Chieftain, Former Minister of Works, and Ex Minister of Defence.\n* Air Vice Marshall Anthony Okpere, Former Minister of Aviation\n* Cardinal Anthony Olubunmi Okojie, Advocate of the poor and Former Catholic Archbishop of Lagos SEE\n* Bishop Dr. Matthew Okpebholo, Philanthropist, Business Icon and Presiding Bishop, CGMI, Uromi\n* Prince Cyprian Imobhio, Philanthropist and Business Mogul\n* Chief Alhaji Musa Isiwele, Business Tycoon and National President, Road Transport Employees Association of Nigeria(RTREAN)\n* Rt. Hon. Barr. Friday Itulah ( KSM, JP) Politician, Former Speaker EDHA and former member, Federal House of Representatives\n* Prof. Julius Okojie, Former Executive Secretary, National Universities Commission and Former Vice Chancellor, Onabisi Onabanjo University\n* Prince Benedict Ewohime, Philanthropist and Business man\n* Prince Joe Okojie, Political Figure and Philanthropist\n* Prince Odi Okojie, Business man and Philanthropist\n\n\n<br />\n==Religion==\nThe people of Esan North-East include [[Christians]], [[Muslim]]s and African traditionalists. Before the era of the white (Europeans), there existed some of the oldest examples in Africa of [[African traditional religion]].\n\nIn 1908, Christianity came to [[Uromi]] in Esan North-East through the evangelism of a Roman Catholic priest Rev. Fr. Joseph Corbeau, a European missionary who was residing then at [[Ubiaja]] (Seat of [[Esan-South-East]] Local Government Area). The people of Uromi, in support of the traditional monarch [[Ogbidi Okojie]], accepted the new religion and after a period of catechetical instruction and evangelism, built a church on land donated by the monarch and his council of Chiefs.\n\n<br />\n== See also ==\n*[[Esan people]]\n*[[Local Government Areas of Nigeria]]\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{LGAs and communities of Edo State}}\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Local Government Areas in Edo State]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Edo State]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          =Esan North-East\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = [[Local Government Areas of Nigeria|LGA]]\n|motto                  =\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            =\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_mapsize=\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       ={{flag|Nigeria}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[States of Nigeria|State]] \n|subdivision_name1      =[[Edo State]]\n|subdivision_type2      =Capital\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      = \n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =  \n|established_date       = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           =\n|area_land_km2            =\n|population_as_of               =2006\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone               =[[West Africa Time|WAT]]\n|utc_offset             = +1\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = \n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       =  \n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Esan North-East''' ([[Uromi]]/[[Uzea]]) is a town and [[Local Government Area]] located in [[Edo state]] of Nigeria with an estimated population of 119,346.<ref>[http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/Connections/Pop2006.pdf 2006 National Census (Nigeria)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704042011/http://www.nigerianstat.gov.ng/Connections/Pop2006.pdf |date=July 4, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n<br />\n==Geography==\nEsan North-East is bordered with [[Atani]] by [[Ubiaja]], [[Ebhoiyi]] by [[Igueben]], [[Ivue]] and [[Obeidu]] by [[Irrua]], [[Uzea]] by [[Afemai]], [[Amendokhian]] by [[Ugboha]] with towns in all its surroundings.\n\n<br />\n==Government==\nThe Esan North-East Local Government Area is divided into two constituencies. Constituency 1 comprises Wards 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5, while constituency 2 comprises Wards 6, 7, 8, 9, and 10, making a total of 10 (ten) political wards represented by two representatives in the [[Edo State House of Assembly]].\n\nEsan North-East is a Local Government Area located in Edo state of Nigeria with an estimated population of 119,346.(2006 Census). The figures are believed to be much more higher than that now. The headquarters of Esan North East is Uromi. According to Wikipedia, Uromi is the largest and most populated Town in Esan Land, and the second fastest growing town in Edo State.\n\n<br />\n== Political Structure ==\nEsan North East has eleven political wards and two state constituencies (two state House of Assembly seats). Constituency 1 is made up of Ward 1 to 5 while Constituency 2 consists of Ward 6 to Ward 11.\n<br />\n<br />\n== Traditional Kingdoms ==\nEsan North East is made up of two gazetted kingdoms and they are:\n\n* Uromi Kingdom\n* Uzea Kingdom\n* Uromi Kingdom has ten wards(Ward 1, 2, 3, 4 ,5, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11) while Uzea Occupies one ward (Ward 6)\n\n\n== Economy ==\nUromi is the commercial hub of Esan Land.The main town popularly referred to as Garage is the commercial nerve centre. The Uromi main market boom with commercial transactions of various kinds every day, all year round, including public holidays and yuletide. Aside Garage, a huge chunk of Esan North East\n\npopulace are predominantly farmers.\n<br />\n<br />\n== Education ==\nEsan North East has the following higher institutions of learning\n\n* The National Institute of Construction Technology Uromi.\n* St Camilus School of Midwifery Uromi\n* National Open University Uromi Study Centre\n* Palm City Polytechnic Uromi\n\nApart from the above, the current best secondary school in Nigeria is situated in Uromi Town. Lumen Christi International High School Uromi was rated by WAEC as the best secondary school in Nigeria on account of the school's excellent performance in the 2016/2017 WASSCE.\n<br />\n<br />\n== Health ==\nThe Uromi Central Hospital(formerly General Hospital) was established to meet the health needs of the people. Aside the Central Hospital, there are government owned health centres and private medical outfits across the LGA including St. Camilus Hospital, Oriafo Hospital, Udegbe Medical Centre to mention but a few.\n<br />At medical zone Uromi, Esan North East LGA Central Hospital Uromi . \n<br />\n== Notable Citizens from Esan North East ==\n\n\nEsan North-East has produced well-known individuals who are popular in both state and national level. These include:\n\n*[[Chief Anthony Enahoro]] - one of Nigeria\u2019s foremost anti-colonial and pro-democracy activists\n* Archbishop Ekpu\n* Cardinal [[Anthony Olubunmi Okogie]]\n* High Chief Dr. Tony Anenih (CFR), (Iyasele of Esanland)- A strong leader of the ruling PDP. Elder Statesman, Former Minister of Works/Housing, and the Prime Minister of Esan Land.\n*Rtd, Air Vice Marshal Anthony Ebehijele Okpere\n* Ehia Olu. AKHABUE\n* Pastor Raymond Okpere\n* Professor, Mike Obadan\n*Professor, E. Okoeguale.\n*Architect Mike Onolemhenmhen (Former Minister Of Works)\n*[[South-South_Nigeria_Rugby_Football_Federation|Flourish Itulua-Abumere]]\n* Dr. Joseph Itotoh (Former Minister for State, Internal Affairs)\n\n* Chief Arc. Dr. Mike Onolememen, Political Chieftain, Former Minister of Works, and Ex Minister of Defence.\n* Air Vice Marshall Anthony Okpere, Former Minister of Aviation\n* Cardinal Anthony Olubunmi Okojie, Advocate of the poor and Former Catholic Archbishop of Lagos SEE\n* Bishop Dr. Matthew Okpebholo, Philanthropist, Business Icon and Presiding Bishop, CGMI, Uromi\n* Prince Cyprian Imobhio, Philanthropist and Business Mogul\n* Chief Alhaji Musa Isiwele, Business Tycoon and National President, Road Transport Employees Association of Nigeria(RTREAN)\n* Rt. Hon. Barr. Friday Itulah ( KSM, JP) Politician, Former Speaker EDHA and former member, Federal House of Representatives\n* Prof. Julius Okojie, Former Executive Secretary, National Universities Commission and Former Vice Chancellor, Onabisi Onabanjo University\n* Prince Benedict Ewohime, Philanthropist and Business man\n* Prince Joe Okojie, Political Figure and Philanthropist\n* Prince Odi Okojie, Business man and Philanthropist\n\n\n<br />\n==Religion==\nThe people of Esan North-East include [[Christians]], [[Muslim]]s and African traditionalists. Before the era of the white (Europeans), there existed some of the oldest examples in Africa of [[African traditional religion]].\n\nIn 1908, Christianity came to [[Uromi]] in Esan North-East through the evangelism of a Roman Catholic priest Rev. Fr. Joseph Corbeau, a European missionary who was residing then at [[Ubiaja]] (Seat of [[Esan-South-East]] Local Government Area). The people of Uromi, in support of the traditional monarch [[Ogbidi Okojie]], accepted the new religion and after a period of catechetical instruction and evangelism, built a church on land donated by the monarch and his council of Chiefs.\n\n<br />\n== See also ==\n*[[Esan people]]\n*[[Local Government Areas of Nigeria]]\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{LGAs and communities of Edo State}}\n{{coord missing|Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Local Government Areas in Edo State]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Edo State]]\n", "name_user": "Oziomoluabi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page":